	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Concerns remain over Sahel food supplies</h1>

			
			<h4>
												22 July 2012
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>An inter-agency report was published on 31 May by agencies including West African farmers’ organisation ROPPA, Oxfam and others. The report argues that although trade in food products in the Sahel does not appear to be experiencing any major disruptions at the moment, it still faces significant shortcomings, especially in the central basin (Mali, Burkina Faso), but also in the wider region (Togo, Ghana and Côte d’Ivoire). This complicates trade in foodstuffs from surplus to deficit areas.</p><p>The problems arising from conflicts in the region are compounded by the trade restrictions adopted by Mali and Burkina Faso which were intended to ease price pressures. These policy measures sit uneasily with commitments made in November 2011 in the Charter for the Prevention and Management of Food Crises. In Burkina Faso, the export of grains has been banned since December 2011. Contrary to the hoped-for effect, this decision seems to have cut the availability of millet in the major markets in Burkina Faso, especially in Ouagadougou, as they are usually supplied by traders bringing in grain to re-export to neighbouring countries further inland.</p><p>In Mali, grain exports are subject to a permit that is granted on a case-by-case basis, causing a backlog in applications and increasing the cost of transport to the deficit areas in neighbouring countries. These restrictions have significantly reduced transfers of grain to the north-eastern part of Niger (Tillaberi), a structurally vulnerable area dependent on transfers from national surplus areas and the closest cross-border markets.</p><p>The low capacity of the trade systems (in terms of storage, transport, networks and administration of cross-border trade) further compound problems faced in moving grains from food-surplus to food-deficit areas.</p><p>It is also likely that supplies to the Sahel belt of Chad will run up against the problem of a lack of trade financing. Increases in the retail price of fuel in Nigeria (+50% between December 2011 and January 2012) are also affecting food transport costs in Niger and Chad.</p><p>In view of these issues, the inter-agency briefing note calls for a range of short-term measures from governments and the international community. These include:</p>
<ul>

<li>focusing on transfers of income to vulnerable groups and supporting income-generating activities (e.g. loans, casual labour) in areas where markets are adequately supplied (in terms of quantities and affordable prices); </li>

<li>facilitating intra-regional grain trade through the lifting of border closures, combating informal barriers to trade, eliminating taxes (VAT) on animal feed and grain imports, and/or subsidising imports from the sub-region;</li>

<li>supporting small businesses in supplying deficit areas through provision of credit and supporting storage capacity in the medium term;</li>

<li>avoiding any further undermining of local supply availability by making major humanitarian grain purchases locally; </li>

<li>supporting the purchase and distribution of animal fodder in zones affected by chronic pasture shortages. </li>

</ul>
<p>In the medium term, it is argued that member states and ECOWAS should strengthen market regulatory capacities by:</p>
<ul>

<li>developing and rapidly implementing the ECOWAS food security storage strategy;</li>

<li>supporting the (re)constitution of food stocks at national and regional levels and ensuring their effective use in regulating prices and addressing food security needs;</li>

<li>ensuring the concerted use of tariffs and other trade measures to combat price volatility.</li>

</ul>

		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>Oxfam, ROPPA <i>et al</i>. ‘Sahel markets under pressure’, <i>Inter-agency briefing note</i>, 31 May 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://www.oxfam.org/sites/www.oxfam.org/files/bn-sahel-markets-under-pressure-31052012-en_0.pdf" target="_self">http://www.oxfam.org/sites/www.oxfam.org/files/bn-sahel-markets-under-pr...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Facilitating intra-regional trade in grain is not just about ending formal border closures, but rather getting to grips with the many barriers to trade in West Africa as a result of regional trade policy commitments that remain largely unimplemented. According to a World Bank analytical study published in June 2011 on the scheme for the harmonised implementation of the texts governing regional trade in West Africa, the removal of barriers to trade is far from being achieved at the borders of the various WAEMU and ECOWAS states (see <i>Agritrade </i>article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Topics/ACP-FTAs/Non-implementation-of-commitments-and-complex-procedures-hold-back-intra-regional-trade-in-Ghana-and-Nigeria" target="_blank">Non-implementation of commitments and complex procedures hold back intra...</a>’, 29 July 2012).</p><p>As highlighted by a World Bank paper in March 2012 analysing trade in ECOWAS, complex cross-border procedures, red tape and the complexities of the mechanism used to allow free trade in originating goods all mean that ‘intra-regional trade is not duty- or quota-free, and borders present substantial barriers to regional integration’ (see same&nbsp;<i>Agritrade</i> article).</p><p>The prevailing view among business operators in the region is that trade restrictions have a serious impact on regional trade, business costs and market access.</p><p>If the critical challenge of leveraging private sector investment in support of intra-regional agro-food chains is to be met, then various barriers need to be overcome. In particular in this context, it should be noted that ECOWAS Trade Liberalisation Scheme commitments specifically exclude regional products from any quantitative restrictions introduced by member governments,</p><p>Implementing existing trade policy commitments would appear to significantly reduce transaction costs, helping to mitigate rising prices and the worst effects of price volatility. It would also lay the foundation for further infrastructure investments (e.g. in roads and storage), which would in turn further reduce transaction costs and facilitate the movement of basic foodstuffs from food-surplus to food-deficit areas across West Africa.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
